The anti-fouling performance of the as-prepared membranes was evaluated by a fouling-cleaning cycle test. Before the test, the initial water flux (J

                           0
                        ) was measured with DI water as feed at 70 °C for 60 min. Then, the humic acid aqueous solution (3000 ppm) was used as the feed in the fouling test. After 60 min of PV operation, the feed was switched to DI water for the cleaning process. The fouling-cleaning cycle was repeated 5 times, and the water flux in the cleaning process was recorded as the recovered flux. The optical coherence tomography (OCT, Ganymede II, Thorlabs GmbH) was applied to monitor the fouling development under crossflow circulation.

The surface chemical compositions of the fabricated TFC and ACQD-TFN membranes were investigated by ATR-FTIR (Fig. 5
                        ). Unsurprisingly, the ACQD-TFN membranes have a very similar FTIR spectra to the TFC membrane due to the high overlap in the functional groups on the ACQDs and polyamide layer. The hydrophilicity of the membrane surface was determined by static water contact angle. As shown in Fig. 6
                        , the water contact angle continuously decreased from 66.6° (TFC) to 47.6° (50wt%ACQD-TFN) as the ACQD content was increased from 0 to 50 wt%. The enhanced surface hydrophilicity is due to the incorporation of ACQDs, which possess abundant hydrophilic functional groups such as hydroxyl, carboxyl, and amine. Furthermore, the incorporation of ACQDs in the polyamide layer increased membrane wettability by constructing extra water channels [52].

The fouling resistance of the fabricated ACQD-TFN membrane was evaluated with humic acid (HA) as the organic contaminant in the feed solution. Fig. 10
                         shows the results of the 5-cycles of fouling and cleaning tests performed over a total period of 11 h. The initial water flux of the ACQD-TFN and TFC membranes were acquired with DI water as feed during the first 60 min, then the feed was switched to a 2000 ppm HA solution for the fouling test. After 60 min of fouling, the membrane was cleaned by changing feed to DI water for another 60 min. The results showed that the water flux of the ACQD-TFN and TFC membranes initially showed a sudden decrease by 21% and 32%, respectively, when the feed was switched to the HA solution, which could be ascribed to the immediate adsorption of the foulants on the membrane surface [70]. After cleaning by the DI water, the ACQD-TFN and TFC membranes' fluxes recovered to 96% and 92%, respectively, after 5 fouling-cleaning cycles (as shown in Fig. 11
                        ), and the final water recovery rate recorded 91% and 68%, respectively. It is worth noting that we did not introduce any cleaning detergents and only used DI water in the cleaning cycle, which makes it natural for the pollutants to gradually accumulate on the membrane surface. The development of foulant layers on the membranes' surfaces was further revealed by optical coherence tomography (OCT) technology (as shown in Fig. S4) [71]. The simple cleaning process we applied removed most of the foulants on the ACQD-TFN membrane and recovered flux to 91%, while the TFC membrane showed poor anti-fouling performance with a flux recovery rate of only 68%. The enhanced fouling resistance of the ACQD-TFN membrane can be attributed to the increased hydrophilicity acquired by introducing the hydrophilic groups (e.g. NH, -COOH, and -OH) on the ACQD nanoparticles.
